 qui ne se laisse pas réduire à une notion purement punitive.  aThis study seeks to clarify the principle of talionic justice beginning with its first historical manifestations in the legal systems of the Ancient Near East. Itattempts to show that talionic justice was not simply a theory of punishment, but also existed as a restorative justice model. The argument for this interpretation of the talionic formula rests on analysis of the salient Biblical verses in the light of the cuneiform models and also utilizes more recent evidence from the Mediterranean region dating from the first centuries of the Christian era. Talionic justice emerges as a complete and constructive principle of justice from the time of its inception, one that cannot be reducedsolely to its punitive elements.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn French.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aLex talioniszMiddle EastxHistory. 0aPunishmentzMiddle EastxHistory. 4aBundesbuch. 4aCodex Hammurabi. 4aTalion. 4aVergeltung. 4aZwölftafelgesetze. 7aRELIGION / Biblical Criticism & Interpretation / Old Testament.2bisacsh  aBook of the Covenant.  aCode of Hammurabi.  aLaw of the Twelve Tables.  aRetributive Justice.  aTalion.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDGBA Classics and Near East Studies 2000 - 2014z9783110636178oZDB-23-GCN08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDGBA Theology and Religious Studies 2000 - 2014z9783110638165oZDB-23-GTR08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertE-BOOK GESAMTPAKET / COMPLETE PACKAGE 2011z9783110261189oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertE-BOOK PAKET THEOLOGIE/RELIGIONSWISS./JUDAISTIK  2011z9783110261271oZDB-23-DGF0 cprintz978311026450040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978311026451740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110264517423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/97